1
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:14,497
Most productivity apps help us do more.
My problem is the opposite.

2
00:00:14,497 --> 00:00:18,994
I’m Yoshie Yamada, a novelist and freelance writer.

3
00:00:18,994 --> 00:00:23,491
I can turn even a hospital room into a workspace.

4
00:00:23,491 --> 00:00:27,088
So I needed a brake: Maybe Tomorrow.

5
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:32,869
I name one activity and answer seven scored questions,
plus a final check about making it smaller.

6
00:00:32,869 --> 00:00:37,739
The rules are fixed and transparent,
with three verdicts—

7
00:00:37,739 --> 00:00:43,420
no generated advice or hidden confidence score.

8
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:49,833
On an overfull day, another side project
gets “Maybe tomorrow.”

9
00:00:49,833 --> 00:00:54,694
The app checks all 78,125 scored answer combinations

10
00:00:54,694 --> 00:01:01,500
and shows the smallest changes needed for another result,
while leaving my original answers untouched.

11
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,692
Calendar context is optional. I can import an ICS file,
a calendar export ZIP,

12
00:01:07,692 --> 00:01:13,384
or use a fictional sample.
Everything stays in this browser.

13
00:01:13,384 --> 00:01:19,076
The app uses event times, but only I decide what must stay,

14
00:01:19,076 --> 00:01:24,767
what can move or shrink, what takes energy,
and what protects recovery.

15
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:31,270
For one more hour of writing,
it considers only changes I have allowed.

16
00:01:31,270 --> 00:01:36,540
Here, shortening the fictional gym visit
creates a continuous hour.

17
00:01:36,540 --> 00:01:42,688
Fixed commitments and recovery stay protected,
and the source calendar is never edited.

18
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,091
I didn’t write or edit code.

19
00:01:48,091 --> 00:01:54,227
I shaped the product with my AI partner, Templex Tsukino,
using GPT-5.6 Sol.

20
00:01:54,227 --> 00:01:58,318
Templex turned our conversations into

21
00:01:58,318 --> 00:02:02,409
signed specifications, rules,
privacy boundaries, and review criteria.

22
00:02:02,409 --> 00:02:06,500
Codex implemented, tested, documented,
and deployed the browser app.

23
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:11,574
I directed part of the build from my phone
at an internet cafe and a gym.

24
00:02:11,574 --> 00:02:16,148
Codex completed release work while I enjoyed the festival.
That wasn’t lost productivity.

25
00:02:16,148 --> 00:02:19,960
It was the point.
Maybe Tomorrow. was built with AI,

26
00:02:19,960 --> 00:02:24,533
but no AI reads your calendar.
We can see the time.

27
00:02:24,533 --> 00:02:29,107
Only you know what it means.
